Abstraction in C# – Full Summary
✅ What is Abstraction?

Abstraction means hiding internal implementation and showing only essential details to the user.

👉 Simple meaning:
You know what to do, but not how it works internally.

🔹 Real-life Example:

ATM machine → you insert card, enter PIN, withdraw money

You don’t know internal banking process → that’s abstraction

✅ How Abstraction is Achieved in C#

In C#, abstraction is achieved using:

Abstract Classes

Interfaces

🔷 1. Abstract Class
✅ Definition:

An abstract class is a class that cannot be instantiated and may contain:

Abstract methods (no body)

Normal methods (with body)

🔹 Syntax:
abstract class Animal
{
    public abstract void Sound(); // no body

    public void Eat()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Animal is eating");
    }
}
🔹 Implementation:
class Dog : Animal
{
    public override void Sound()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Dog barks");
    }
}
✅ Key Points:

Cannot create object of abstract class

Must use inheritance

Abstract methods must be overridden

Can have constructor

Can have fields

🔷 2. Interface
✅ Definition:

An interface is a contract that contains only:

Method declarations

No implementation (by default)

🔹 Syntax:
interface IAnimal
{
    void Sound();
}
🔹 Implementation:
class Dog : IAnimal
{
    public void Sound()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Dog barks");
    }
}
✅ Key Points:

No method body (before C# 8 mostly)

Supports multiple inheritance

Cannot have constructors

All methods are public by default

🔥 Abstract Class vs Interface
Feature	Abstract Class	Interface
Methods	Both abstract & normal	Only abstract
Constructors	Yes	No
Multiple Inherit	No	Yes
Access Modifiers	Any	Public by default
🔷 Why Use Abstraction?

✅ Reduces complexity
✅ Improves security (hide details)
✅ Makes code maintainable
✅ Supports loose coupling

🔥 Important Interview Q&A (VERY IMPORTANT)
❓1. What is abstraction in C#?

Answer:
Abstraction is the process of hiding implementation details and showing only essential features using abstract classes and interfaces.

❓2. How do you achieve abstraction in C#?

Answer:
By using:

Abstract classes

Interfaces

❓3. Can we create object of abstract class?

Answer:
No, we cannot create an object of an abstract class.

❓4. What is an abstract method?

Answer:
A method without body declared using abstract keyword and must be implemented in derived class.

❓5. Why do we use abstract class?

Answer:
To provide common base functionality and enforce derived classes to implement specific methods.

❓6. What is interface in C#?

Answer:
An interface is a contract that defines methods which must be implemented by a class.

❓7. Difference between abstract class and interface?

Answer:
Abstract class can have both implemented and non-implemented methods, while interface contains only method declarations.

❓8. Can abstract class have constructor?

Answer:
Yes.

❓9. Can interface have constructor?

Answer:
No.

❓10. Can a class inherit multiple abstract classes?

Answer:
No, C# does not support multiple inheritance for classes.

❓11. Can a class implement multiple interfaces?

Answer:
Yes.

❓12. When to use abstract class vs interface?

Answer:

Use abstract class → when classes share common code

Use interface → when different classes follow same contract

❓13. What is method overriding?

Answer:
Providing implementation of abstract method in derived class using override.

❓14. Can we have fields in interface?

Answer:
No (only constants allowed).

❓15. What is the main advantage of abstraction?

Answer:
It hides complexity and improves code reusability.

